{"title_page": "Western City Gate", "text_new": "{{short description|Building in Belgrade, Serbia}}\n{{More citations needed|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                = Western City Gate<br>Genex Tower\n| native_name         = \u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u043a\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430<br>Zapadna kapija Beograda\n| native_name_lang    = sr\n| alternate_names     = Genex Tower\n| image               = Jugotours Beograd Dec 2003.jpg\n| image_size          = 200px\n| caption             = Western City Gate in winter\n| location            = [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]]\n| location_country    = Serbia\n| coordinates         = {{Coord|44|49|13|N|20|24|17|E|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map         = Serbia Belgrade\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location within Belgrade\n| completion_date     = {{start date and age|1979}}\n| architect           = [[Mihajlo Mitrovi\u0107]]\n| owner               = [[Government of Serbia]]\n| floor_area          = {{convert|16000|m2|sqft|abbr=on}}\n| floor_count         = 36\n| map_type            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = Location within Serbia\n| building_type       = Office and residential\n| architectural_style = [[Brutalism]]\n| roof                = {{convert|154|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| main_contractor     = \n| developer           = \n}}\n'''Western City Gate''' ({{lang-sr|\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430|Zapadna Kapija Beograda}}), also known as the '''Genex Tower''' ({{lang-sr|\u041a\u0443\u043b\u0430 \u0413\u0435\u043d\u0435\u043a\u0441|Kula Geneks}}), is a 36-[[storey]] [[skyscraper]] in [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]], which was designed in 1977 by {{Interlanguage link multi|Mihajlo Mitrovi\u0107|fr}} in the [[brutalist]] style.<ref>{{cite web|title=Genex Tower, Belgrade|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/110978/genex-tower-belgrade-serbia|website=EMPORIS|accessdate=22 July 2017}}</ref>  It is formed by two towers connected with a two-storey bridge and [[revolving restaurant]] at the top. It is {{convert|117|m|abbr=on}} tall<ref name=arhi/> (with restaurant {{convert|135|-|140|m|abbr=on}}) and is the second-tallest high-rise in Belgrade after [[U\u0161\u0107e Tower]].\n\nThe building is designed to resemble a high-rise gate greeting people arriving in the city from the West (the road from [[Belgrade Nikola Tesla Airport]] to the city centre leads this way). Disputed and criticized during the designing and construction process, the building is today a dominant landmark in Belgrade.<ref name=arhi/>\n\nOne of the towers was occupied by the state-owned Genex Group. The tower got its popular name \"Genex\" after this group, while its official title remains Western City Gate. The second, taller tower, is residential. The tower formerly occupied by the Genex company is empty, while the residential tower is still home to scores of people. The revolving restaurant above it stopped turning.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brutalist concrete of old Yugoslavia inspires new generation |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-46960948 |accessdate=13 October 2019 |work=BBC News |date=28 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Location ==\nThe building is located in the municipality of [[New Belgrade]], in the 41-43 ''Narodnih heroja'' Street. It is actually situated at the corner of the street and the [[European route E75]]. West of the gate are the neighborhoods of [[Studentski Grad (Belgrade)|Studentski Grad]] and [[To\u0161in Bunar]] while [[Fontana, Belgrade|Fontana]] is to the north. In the New Belgrade's blocks numeration system, the building belongs to the Block 33.<ref>{{cite book | author = Tamara Marinkovi\u0107-Rado\u0161evi\u0107 | title = Beograd - plan i vodi\u010d |date = 2007 |publisher = Geokarta | location = Belgrade |isbn = 86-459-0006-8 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title = Beograd - plan grada | date = 2006 | publisher = M@gic M@p | location = Smedrevska Palanka | isbn = 86-83501-53-1 }}</ref><ref name=arhi>{{cite news | author = Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | title = \u0410\u0440\u0445\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0435 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u0448\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443 \u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u0435 \u043a\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0458\u0435 | trans-title = Architects ask for the protection of the Western Gate | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 8 May 2019 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/429066/Beograd/Arhitekte-traze-zastitu}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn the late 1960s, architect {{ill|Mihajlo Mitrovi\u0107|sr}} was given a task of projecting a 12-floor building and the head offices of the local community of Sutjeska, a sub-municipal administrative unit, on ''Narodnih heroja'' Street. Mitrovi\u0107 suggested two connected and much taller buildings which would make a recognizable symbol of the capital city. A fierce opposition, disagreements and disputes ensued, but Mitrovi\u0107 was persistent in his idea, giving detailed and exhaustive explanations in front of the numerous commissions. He was finally given the green light and the foundations were laid in 1971.<ref name=Politika>{{Citation | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Lo\u0161a izolacija, podzemne vode i manjak para i u \"zlatno doba\" | trans-title = Bad insulation, groundwater and lack of funds even in the \"golden age\" | newspaper = [[Politika]] | language = Serbian | date = 5 November 2017 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/392033/Lo-sa-izo-la-ci-ja-pod-zem-ne-vo-de-i-ma-njak-pa-ra-i-u-zlat-no-do-ba }}</ref> The towers were built by the \"Rad\" construction company.\n\nNevertheless, the project met with distrust and was disputed all the time the construction was on.<ref name=arhi/> But the opposition continued in the next years. Even in the 2010s, a famous caricature by [[Ivo Ku\u0161ani\u0107]] in the daily [[Politika]] is still being mentioned and reproduced. It shows a gallows next to the building and the text: Who are these gallows for? For the architect!<ref name=Politika/>\n\n== Architecture ==\nThe two towers which make the building are not the same height. The higher one is a residential tower with 30 floors, while the lower is a business one with 26 floors. The bridge connects them at the 26th floor. The revolving restaurant built at the top never functioned. The building is {{convert|117.76|m|abbr=on}} tall.<ref name=arhi/><ref>{{cite news | author = Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | title = Beogradsko nebo otvoreno za oblakodere | trans-title = Belgrade sky open for skyscrapers | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 21 September 2014 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/305777/Beogradsko-nebo-otvoreno-za-oblakodere}}</ref>\n\nThe building was designed in the [[Brutalist architecture|brutalist]] style, with some elements of [[Structuralism (architecture)|structuralism]] and [[Constructivism (art)|constructivism]]. It is considered a prime representative of the brutalist architecture in Serbia and one of the best of its style built in the 1960s and the 1970s in the world. The treatment of the form and details is slightly associating the building with [[postmodernism]] and is today one of the rare surviving representatives of this style's early period in Serbia. The artistic expression of the gate marked an entire era in Serbian architecture.\n<ref name=arhi/>\n\n=== Mural ===\nIn 1979, Lazar Vujaklija painted a mural at the entrance. The mural covers the fa\u00e7ade and the ceiling above the entrance. It was one of the first murals in Belgrade, predated by the 1970 mural painted on a building in the [[Bulevar kralja Aleksandra|Bulevar Revolucije]], also done by Vujaklija. Another work was added in the 2010s, described by the architects as a \"graffiti, which is unsuitable and not a work of art\". After a reaction from the architects, the author of the graffiti decided to paint it over, in an agreement with Mihajlo Mitrovi\u0107's daughter who inherited the [[author's rights]].<ref name=arhi/><ref>{{cite news | author = Ana Vukovi\u0107 | title = Muralu u Raji\u0107evoj vra\u0107ena nekada\u0161nja lepota | trans-title = Former beauty restored to the mural in Raji\u0107eva | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 13 September 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/411132/Muralu-u-Rajicevoj-vracena-nekadasnja-lepota}}</ref>\n\n== Protection ==\nThe building is placed under the preliminary protection. It means it should be treated as if it were protected until the final decision about the protection is made. Association of Serbian Architects in 2019 filed a motion for Western City Gate to become a fully protected [[cultural monument]].<ref name=arhi/>\n\n== Local community ==\nThe local community of Sutjeska had a population of 5,067 in 1981<ref>{{cite book|title=Osnovni skupovi stanovni\u0161tva u zemlji \u2013 SFRJ, SR i SAP, op\u0161tine i mesne zajednice 31.03.1981, tabela 191|date=1983|publisher=Savezni zavod za statistiku (txt file)}}</ref> and 5,187 in 1991.<ref>{{cite book|title=Stanovni\u0161tvo prema migracionim obele\u017ejima \u2013 SFRJ, SR i SAP, op\u0161tine i mesne zajednice 31.03.1991, tabela 018|date=|publisher=Savezni zavod za statistiku (txt file)}}</ref> By the 2002 census, it was renamed to the Local Community of Western Gate, after the building, and had a population of 4,278.<ref>{{cite book|title=Popis stanovni\u0161tva po mesnim zajednicama, Saop\u0161tenje 40/2002, page 4|date=26 July 2002|publisher=Zavod za informatiku i statistiku grada Beograda}}</ref> It was later annexed to the neighboring local community of Fontana.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n| bgcolor=\"#ECECEC\" | \n<gallery widths=150px perrow=\"4\" style=\"font-size: small; line-height: 130%;\">\nGenex Tower.jpg\nNovi Beograd - West Gate 01.jpg\nNovi Beograd - West Gate 03.jpg\nGenex Tower, looking up..jpg\n</gallery>\n|}\n</center>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Gates of Belgrade]]\n* [[List of tallest buildings in Serbia]]\n* [[List of tallest structures in former Yugoslavia]]\n* [[Trellick Tower]] and [[Balfron Tower]], blocks of flats in [[London]] of similar design\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commonscat-inline|Genex Tower}}\n\n{{Belgrade Architecture}}\n\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1980]]\n[[Category:Residential buildings completed in 1980]]\n[[Category:Brutalist architecture]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures with revolving restaurants]]\n[[Category:Gates]]\n[[Category:Skyscrapers in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Towers in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Twin towers]]\n[[Category:New Belgrade]]\n\n{{Serbia-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Building in Belgrade, Serbia}}\n{{More citations needed|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                = Western City Gate<br>Genex Tower\n| native_name         = \u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u043a\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430<br>Zapadna kapija Beograda\n| native_name_lang    = sr\n| alternate_names     = Genex Tower\n| image               = Jugotours Beograd Dec 2003.jpg\n| image_size          = 200px\n| caption             = Western City Gate in winter\n| location            = [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]]\n| location_country    = Serbia\n| coordinates         = {{Coord|44|49|13|N|20|24|17|E|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map         = Serbia Belgrade\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location within Belgrade\n| completion_date     = {{start date and age|1979}}\n| architect           = [[Mihajlo Mitrovi\u0107]]\n| owner               = [[Government of Serbia]]\n| floor_area          = {{convert|16000|m2|sqft|abbr=on}}\n| floor_count         = 36\n| map_type            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = Location within Serbia\n| building_type       = Office and residential\n| architectural_style = [[Brutalism]]\n| roof                = {{convert|154|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| main_contractor     = \n| developer           = \n}}\n'''Western City Gate''' ({{lang-sr|\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430|Zapadna Kapija Beograda}}), also known as the '''Genex Tower''' ({{lang-sr|\u041a\u0443\u043b\u0430 \u0413\u0435\u043d\u0435\u043a\u0441|Kula Geneks}}), is a 36-[[storey]] [[skyscraper]] in [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]], which was designed in 1977 by {{Interlanguage link multi|Mihajlo Mitrovi\u0107|fr}} in the [[brutalist]] style.<ref>{{cite web|title=Genex Tower, Belgrade|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/110978/genex-tower-belgrade-serbia|website=EMPORIS|accessdate=22 July 2017}}</ref>  It is formed by two towers connected with a two-storey bridge and [[revolving restaurant]] at the top. It is {{convert|117|m|abbr=on}} tall<ref name=arhi/> (with restaurant {{convert|135|-|140|m|abbr=on}}) and is the second-tallest high-rise in Belgrade after [[U\u0161\u0107e Tower]].\n\nThe building is designed to resemble a high-rise gate greeting people arriving in the city from the West (the road from [[Belgrade Nikola Tesla Airport]] to the city centre leads this way). Disputed and criticized during the designing and construction process, the building is today a dominant landmark in Belgrade.<ref name=arhi/>\n\nOne of the towers was occupied by the state-owned Genex Group. The tower got its popular name \"Genex\" after this group, while its official title remains Western City Gate. The second, taller tower, is residential. The tower formerly occupied by the Genex company is empty, while the residential tower is still home to scores of people. The revolving restaurant above it stopped turning.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brutalist concrete of old Yugoslavia inspires new generation |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-46960948 |accessdate=13 October 2019 |work=BBC News |date=28 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Location ==\nThe building is located in the municipality of [[New Belgrade]], in the 41-43 ''Narodnih heroja'' Street. It is actually situated at the corner of the street and the [[European route E75]]. West of the gate are the neighborhoods of [[Studentski Grad (Belgrade)|Studentski Grad]] and [[To\u0161in Bunar]] while [[Fontana, Belgrade|Fontana]] is to the north. In the New Belgrade's blocks numeration system, the building belongs to the Block 33.<ref>{{cite book | author = Tamara Marinkovi\u0107-Rado\u0161evi\u0107 | title = Beograd - plan i vodi\u010d |date = 2007 |publisher = Geokarta | location = Belgrade |isbn = 86-459-0006-8 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title = Beograd - plan grada | date = 2006 | publisher = M@gic M@p | location = Smedrevska Palanka | isbn = 86-83501-53-1 }}</ref><ref name=arhi>{{cite news | author = Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | title = \u0410\u0440\u0445\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0435 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u0448\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443 \u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u0435 \u043a\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0458\u0435 | trans-title = Architects ask for the protection of the Western Gate | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 8 May 2019 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/429066/Beograd/Arhitekte-traze-zastitu}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn the late 1960s, architect {{ill|Mihajlo Mitrovi\u0107|sr}} was given a task of projecting a 12-floor building and the head offices of the local community of Sutjeska, a sub-municipal administrative unit, on ''Narodnih heroja'' Street. Mitrovi\u0107 suggested two connected and much taller buildings which would make a recognizable symbol of the capital city. A fierce opposition, disagreements and disputes ensued, but Mitrovi\u0107 was persistent in his idea, giving detailed and exhaustive explanations in front of the numerous commissions. He was finally given the green light and the foundations were laid in 1971.<ref name=Politika>{{Citation | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Lo\u0161a izolacija, podzemne vode i manjak para i u \"zlatno doba\" | trans-title = Bad insulation, groundwater and lack of funds even in the \"golden age\" | newspaper = [[Politika]] | language = Serbian | date = 5 November 2017 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/392033/Lo-sa-izo-la-ci-ja-pod-zem-ne-vo-de-i-ma-njak-pa-ra-i-u-zlat-no-do-ba }}</ref> The towers were built by the \"Rad\" construction company.\n\nNevertheless, the project met with distrust and was disputed all the time the construction was on.<ref name=arhi/> But the opposition continued in the next years. Even in the 2010s, a famous caricature by [[Ivo Ku\u0161ani\u0107]] in the daily [[Politika]] is still being mentioned and reproduced. It shows a gallows next to the building and the text: Who are these gallows for? For the architect!<ref name=Politika/>\n\n== Architecture ==\nThe two towers which make the building are not the same height. The higher one is a residential tower with 30 floors, while the lower is a business one with 26 floors. The bridge connects them at the 26th floor. The revolving restaurant built at the top never functioned. The building is {{convert|117.76|m|abbr=on}} tall.<ref name=arhi/><ref>{{cite news | author = Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | title = Beogradsko nebo otvoreno za oblakodere | trans-title = Belgrade sky open for skuscrapers | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 21 September 2014 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/305777/Beogradsko-nebo-otvoreno-za-oblakodere}}</ref>\n\nThe building was designed in the [[Brutalist architecture|brutalist]] style, with some elements of [[Structuralism (architecture)|structuralism]] and [[Constructivism (art)|constructivism]]. It is considered a prime representative of the brutalist architecture in Serbia and one of the best of its style built in the 1960s and the 1970s in the world. The treatment of the form and details is slightly associating the building with [[postmodernism]] and is today one of the rare surviving representatives of this style's early period in Serbia. The artistic expression of the gate marked an entire era in Serbian architecture.\n<ref name=arhi/>\n\n=== Mural ===\nIn 1979, Lazar Vujaklija painted a mural at the entrance. The mural covers the fa\u00e7ade and the ceiling above the entrance. It was one of the first murals in Belgrade, predated by the 1970 mural painted on a building in the [[Bulevar kralja Aleksandra|Bulevar Revolucije]], also done by Vujaklija. Another work was added in the 2010s, described by the architects as a \"graffiti, which is unsuitable and not a work of art\". After a reaction from the architects, the author of the graffiti decided to paint it over, in an agreement with Mihajlo Mitrovi\u0107's daughter who inherited the [[author's rights]].<ref name=arhi/><ref>{{cite news | author = Ana Vukovi\u0107 | title = Muralu u Raji\u0107evoj vra\u0107ena nekada\u0161nja lepota | trans-title = Former beauty restored to the mural in Raji\u0107eva | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 13 September 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/411132/Muralu-u-Rajicevoj-vracena-nekadasnja-lepota}}</ref>\n\n== Protection ==\nThe building is placed under the preliminary protection. It means it should be treated as if it were protected until the final decision about the protection is made. Association of Serbian Architects in 2019 filed a motion for Western City Gate to become a fully protected [[cultural monument]].<ref name=arhi/>\n\n== Local community ==\nThe local community of Sutjeska had a population of 5,067 in 1981<ref>{{cite book|title=Osnovni skupovi stanovni\u0161tva u zemlji \u2013 SFRJ, SR i SAP, op\u0161tine i mesne zajednice 31.03.1981, tabela 191|date=1983|publisher=Savezni zavod za statistiku (txt file)}}</ref> and 5,187 in 1991.<ref>{{cite book|title=Stanovni\u0161tvo prema migracionim obele\u017ejima \u2013 SFRJ, SR i SAP, op\u0161tine i mesne zajednice 31.03.1991, tabela 018|date=|publisher=Savezni zavod za statistiku (txt file)}}</ref> By the 2002 census, it was renamed to the Local Community of Western Gate, after the building, and had a population of 4,278.<ref>{{cite book|title=Popis stanovni\u0161tva po mesnim zajednicama, Saop\u0161tenje 40/2002, page 4|date=26 July 2002|publisher=Zavod za informatiku i statistiku grada Beograda}}</ref> It was later annexed to the neighboring local community of Fontana.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n| bgcolor=\"#ECECEC\" | \n<gallery widths=150px perrow=\"4\" style=\"font-size: small; line-height: 130%;\">\nGenex Tower.jpg\nNovi Beograd - West Gate 01.jpg\nNovi Beograd - West Gate 03.jpg\nGenex Tower, looking up..jpg\n</gallery>\n|}\n</center>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Gates of Belgrade]]\n* [[List of tallest buildings in Serbia]]\n* [[List of tallest structures in former Yugoslavia]]\n* [[Trellick Tower]] and [[Balfron Tower]], blocks of flats in [[London]] of similar design\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commonscat-inline|Genex Tower}}\n\n{{Belgrade Architecture}}\n\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1980]]\n[[Category:Residential buildings completed in 1980]]\n[[Category:Brutalist architecture]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures with revolving restaurants]]\n[[Category:Gates]]\n[[Category:Skyscrapers in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Towers in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Twin towers]]\n[[Category:New Belgrade]]\n\n{{Serbia-stub}}\n", "name_user": "PajaBG", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eArchitecture:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_City_Gate"}
